            "arguments": "{\"content\": \"# MCP Tools Fix - Complete\\n\\n## Bugs Found & Fixed:\\n\\n### Bug #1 (CRITICAL): `_mcp_manager` stored in wrong location\\n- **File:** `tools/__init__.py:185`\\n- **Problem:** The `set_context` handler for `_mcp_manager` was storing it in `globals()[\\\"_MCP_MANAGER\\\"]` but `_mcp_discover` and `_mcp_call` read from `_TOOL_CONTEXT._mcp_manager` via `getattr(_TOOL_CONTEXT, \\\"_mcp_manager\\\", None)`\\n- **Result:** `_mcp_manager` was **always None** at call time, so `mcp_discover` always returned \\\"No MCP manager configured\\\" even when MCP servers were configured\\n- **Fix:** Changed handler to `lambda ctx, v: setattr(ctx, \\\"_mcp_manager\\\", v)` so it's stored on `_TOOL_CONTEXT` where the read side looks for it\\n\\n### Bug #2: `_mcp_discover` iterates dict keys as dicts\\n- **File:** `tools/mcp_client.py:665-669`\\n- **Problem:** `conn._tools` is `dict[str, dict]` (name \u2192 schema). Iterating with `for tool in conn._tools` gives string keys, but code called `tool.get('name','?')` which would crash with AttributeError\\n- **Fix:** Changed to `for tool_name, tool_info in conn._tools.items()` with correct variable usage\\n\\n### Verification:\\n- All 50 test_mcp.py tests pass\\n- `_MCP_MANAGER` global has no other references (safe to change)\\n\"}"
