y [no sub-agent completed within 10s. still running: ['a62d7ec4] \\\\u2014 Tool 'collect_any' failed 1 time(s) with pattern 'no sub-agent completed within 10s. still running: ['a62d7ec4': No sub-agent completed within 10s. Still running: ['a62d7ec4', '2094ebde', '199ff3b3', 'e3a336fd']. Use collect_any again to retry.\\\\n- [error] Tool failure: run_tests [exit_code=4] \\\\u2014 Tool 'run_tests' failed 1 time(s) with pattern 'exit_code=4': exit_code=4\\\\n- [error] Tool failure: verify [verify is restricted to the orchestrator. sub-agents must no] \\\\u2014 Tool 'verify' failed 1 time(s) with pattern 'verify is restricted to the orchestrator. sub-agents must no': verify is restricted to the orchestrator. Sub-agents must not run tests.\\\\n- [error] Tool failure: run_tests [run_tests is restricted to the orchestrator. sub-agents must] \\\\u2014 Tool 'run_tests' failed 1 time(s) with pattern 'run_tests is restricted to the orchestrator. sub-agents must': run_tests is restricted to the orchestrator. Sub-agents must not run tests.\\\\n\\\"\\n    },\\n    {\\n      \\\"role\\\": \\\"user\\\",\\n      \\\"content\\\": \\\"[Earlier context summary] Here's the summary of this conversation excerpt:\\\\n\\\\n**Key facts learned:** An `api_error.log` file exists at `/Users/gabrielmalone/Desktop/api_error.log` (not inside the workspace) containing a **400 error** with message: *\\\\\\\"An assistant message with 'tool_calls' must be followed by tool messages responding to each 'tool_call_id'.\\\\\\\"* This revealed a **path bug** \\\\u2014 the log path `os.path.join(os.path.dirname(__file__), \\\\\\\"..\\\\\\\", \\\\\\\"api_error.log\\\\\\\")` resolves one level *above* the workspace instead of inside it.\\\\n\\\\n**Key decisions made:** The user confirmed they want the MCP/tool-call issue fixed (the error about insufficient tool messages following a `tool_calls`-bearing assistant message).\\\\n\\\\n**Progress:** The assistant traced the codebase across `api.py`, `llm.py`, `mcp_client.py`, and `tools/__init__.py` to understand the M\\\"\\n    },\\n    {\\n      \\\"role\\\": \\\"user\\\",\\n      \\\"content\\\": \\\"look on the web you don't know the problem\\\"\\n    },\\n    {\\n      \\\"role\\\": \\\"assistant\\\",\\n      \\\"content\\\": \\\"You're right, let me search for the actual solution instead of guessing.\\\",\\n      \\\"reasoning_content\\\": \\\"The user is frustrated that I'm spending too long reading code and not making progress. Let me step back and think about what I actually know and what the web might tell me.\\\\n\\\\nThe error in api_error.log is:\\\\n```\\\\n\\\\\\\"An assistant message with 'tool_calls' must be followed by tool messages responding to each 'tool_call_id'. (insufficient tool messages following tool_calls message)\\\\\\\"\\\\n```\\\\n\\\\nThis is a DeepSeek API error. The issue is that in the message payload, there's an assistant message with `tool_calls` but not all tool_call_ids have corresponding tool messages (role: \\\\\\\"tool\\\\\\\") following them before the next assistant message.\\\\n\\\\nLet me search the web for this error pattern and how to fix it.\\\",\\n      \\\"tool_calls\\\": [\\n        {\\n          \\\"id\\\": \\\"call_00_T6Ltte8QGfv8lzEzFZJC2348\\\",\\n          \\\"type\\\": \\\"function\\\",\\n          \\\"function\\\": {\\n            \\\"name\\\": \\\"web_search\\\",\\n            \\\"arguments\\\": \\\"{\\\\\\\"query\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"DeepSeek API \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"insufficient tool messages following tool_calls message\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" error fix\\\\\\\"}\\\"\\n          }\\n        },\\n        {\\n          \\\"id\\\": \\\"call_01_j7xjsXVdtfN5XBeTBrx51239\\\",\\n          \\\"type\\\": \\\"function\\\",\\n          \\\"function\\\": {\\n            \\\"name\\\": \\\"web_search\\\",\\n            \\\"arguments\\\": \\\"{\\\\\\\"query\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"OpenAI API \\\\\\\\\\\\\\\"An assistant message with 'tool_calls' must be followed by tool messages\\\\\\\\\\\\\\\" root cause\\\\\\\"}\\\"\\n          }\\n        }\\n      ]\\n    },\\n    {\\n      \\\"role\\\": \\\"tool\\\",\\n      \\\"tool_call_id\\\": \\\"call_00_T6Ltte8QGfv8lzEzFZJC2348\\\",\\n      \\\"content\\\": \\\"{\\\\\\\"success\\\\\\\": true, \\\\\\\"content\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"1. [BUG] 400 An assistant message with 'tool_calls' must be followed by tool messages responding to each 'tool_call_id'. (insufficient tool messages following tool_calls message) \\\\\\\\u00b7 Issue #1078 \\\\\\\\u00b7 ThinkInAIXYZ/deepchat\\\\\\\\n   https://github.com/ThinkInAIXYZ/deepchat/issues/1078\\\\\\\\n   > ## [BUG] 400 An assistant message with 'tool_calls' must be followed by tool messages responding to each 'tool_call_id'. (insufficient tool messages following tool_calls message)\\\\\\\\n[...]\\\\\\\\n1. \\\\\\\\u5f53\\\\\\\\u5728\\\\\\\\u540c\\\\\\\\u4e00\\\\\\\\u4e2a\\\\\\\\u5bf9\\\\\\\\u8bdd\\\\\\\\u91cc\\\\\\\\uff0c\\\\\\\\u8fde\\\\\\\\u7eed\\\\\\\\u5c1d\\\\\\\\u8bd5\\\\\\\\u8c03\\\\\\\\u7528mcp\\\\\\\\u529f\\\\\\\\u80fd\\\\\\\\uff0c\\\\\\\\u5c31\\\\\\\\u4f1a\\\\\\\\u51fa\\\\\\\\u73b0400 An as\\\\\\\\u2026\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\u2026 (truncated at 5 lines \\\\\\\\u2014 6 total)\\\\\\\"}\\\"\\n    },\\n    {\\n      \\\"role\\\": \\\"tool\\\",\\n      \\\"tool_call_id\\\": \\\"call_01_j7xjsXVdtfN5XBeTBrx51239\\\",\\n      \\\"content\\\": \\\"{\\\\\\\"success\\\\\\\": true, \\\\\\\"content\\\\\\\": \\\\\\\"1. OpenAI tool calls must be followed by tool messages\\\\\\\\n   https://www.joseferben.com/posts/openai-tool-calls-must-be-followed-by-tool-messages\\\\\\\\n   > OpenAI tool calls must be followed by tool messages\\\\\\\\n[...]\\\\\\\\nAn assistant message with \\\\\\\\u2018tool_calls\\\\\\\\u2019 must be followed by tool messages responding to each \\\\\\\\u2018tool_call_id\\\\\\\\u2019. The following tool_call_ids did not have response messages\\\\\\\\n\\\\\\\\u2026 (truncated at 5 lines \\\\\\\\u2014 6 total)\\\\\\\"}\\\"\\n    },\\n    {\\n      \\\"role\\\": \\\"assistant\\\",\\n      \\\"content\\\": \\\"Good findings. The web confirms the root cause: **when streaming tool execution raises an exception, the tool_call_id gets marked as \\\\\\\"executed\\\\\\\" but no result message is appended**, creating an orphaned `tool_calls` entry in the next API call. Let me now trace where the code actually breaks.\\\",\\n      \\\"reasoning_content\\\": \\\"Now I have a much clearer picture. The search results confirm the root cause:\\\\n\\\\n**The 400 \\\\\\\"insufficient tool messages\\\\\\\" error** happens when:\\\\n1. An assistant message with `tool_calls` is in the conversation history but the corresponding tool result messages are missing\\\\n2. Other messages (like another assistant message) appear between the `tool_calls` and tool responses\\\\n3. During streaming, if tool execution is incomplete but the assistant message with tool_calls is already recorded\\\\n\\\\nKey insights from the Codex issue (#7275):\\\\n- \\\\\\\"Incomplete tool calls: When API streaming is interrupted mid-request, the assistant message with tool_calls gets recorded, but tool execution never completes. On retry, this incomplete tool call remains in the history without matching responses.\\\\\\\"\\\\n- \\\\\\\"Sequence violations: During streaming, Codex may record an assistant text message between the tool_calls message and tool responses, breaking the required sequence.\\\\\\\"\\\\n\\\\nAnd from the DeepChat issue:\\\\n- \\\\\\\"There is many 'tool_calls' for 'role': 'assistant' but their responses are put ALL TOGETHER for one 'tool_call_id'\\\\\\\"\\\\n\\\\nNow let me look at the mini_agent code to find where this happens. The key areas to check:\\\\n\\\\n1. **Message cleaning in api.py**: The `_clean_message` function and the incremental cache\\\\n2. **The `_tool_execution_phase` in llm.py**: Where the assistant message and tool results are appended\\\\n3. **The `_on_tool_ready` streaming callback**: Where tools are executed during streaming\\\\n\\\\nLet me look at a specific scenario: the LLM returns an assistant message with multiple `tool_calls`. Some are executed during streaming (`_on_tool_ready`), some are deferred. Then the LLM is called again.\\\\n\\\\nLooking at `_tool_execution_phase`:\\\\n```python\\\\nraw_tool_calls = msg[\\\\\\\"tool_calls\\\\\\\"]\\\\nremaining = [tc for i, tc in enumerate(raw_tool_calls) if i not in executed_tool_indices]\\\\n\\\\nif not remaining:\\\\n    # All tools were already executed during streaming\\\\n    messages.append(msg)\\\\n    for tc, result in deferred_stream_results:\\\\n        _append_tool_result(messages, tc, result, on_tool_end=None, ...)\\\\n    _save_turn_summary(turn_count, msg, deferred_stream_results, messages)\\\\n    return False  # continue the turn loop\\\\n```\\\\n\\\\nWhen `return False`:\\\\n```python\\\\ncontinue_loop = _tool_execution_phase(...)\\\\nif not continue_loop:\\\\n    continue\\\\n```\\\\n\\\\nIt continues the loop, which means it goes back to `_api_call_phase` \\\\u2192 calls the LLM again. At this point, the messages list has:\\\\n1. [previous messages...]\\\\n2. assistant msg with tool_calls\\\\n3. tool msg for each deferred result\\\\n\\\\nThis looks correct. But what if one of the deferred stream results fails silently or is missing?\\\\n\\\\nNow let me look at the `_on_tool_ready` callback:\\\\n```python\\\\ndef _on_tool_ready(tc: dict) -> None:\\\\n    idx = tc.pop(\\\\\\\"_index\\\\\\\", -1)\\\\n    if idx in executed_tool_indices:\\\\n        return\\\\n    executed_tool_indices.add(idx)\\\\n    if cancel_event is not None and cancel_event.is_set():\\\\n        return\\\\n    ...\\\\n    result = execute_tool(tc, write_gate, read_gate, ...)\\\\n    deferred_stream_results.append((tc, result))\\\\n```\\\\n\\\\nIf `execute_tool` raises an exception (like the TypeError from `_mcp_discover`), then:\\\\n1. `executed_tool_indices.add(idx)` has already been called\\\\n2. But `deferred_stream_results.append(...)` never happens\\\\n3. So there's a tool_call_id marked as \\\\\\\"executed\\\\\\\" but no result\\\\n\\\\nWait, but if `execute_tool` raises an exception, it would propagate up through `_on_tool_ready`, through `_parse_stream`, and the stream would break. The `msg` returned would have `_fired_indices` set. But if the exception is caught by `stream.py`'s exception handler (line 139-141), it just prints to stderr and continues.\\\\n\\\\nActually wait, let me re-read the stream.py code carefully:\\\\n\\\\n```python\\\\nif on_tool_ready and idx not in fired_indices:\\\\n    args = tc[\\\\\\\"function\\\\\\\"][\\\\\\\"arguments\\\\\\\"]\\\\n    if args.count(\\\\\\\"{\\\\\\\") == args.count(\\\\\\\"}\\\\\\\") and args.count(\\\\\\\"[\\\\\\\") == args.count(\\\\\\\"]\\\\\\\"):\\\\n        try:\\\\n            json.loads(args)\\\\n            fired_indices.add(idx)\\\\n            ready = dict(tc)\\\\n            ready[\\\\\\\"_index\\\\\\\"] = idx\\\\n            on_tool_ready(ready)\\\\n        except (json.JSONDecodeError, ValueError):\\\\n            pass  # still fragmentary\\\\n```\\\\n\\\\nThe `on_tool_ready(ready)` call is inside a try block that only catches `json.JSONDecodeError` and `ValueError`. If `on_tool_ready` raises a `TypeError`, it would propagate to the OUTER exception handler:\\\\n\\\\n```python\\\\nexcept (json.JSONDecodeError, KeyError, TypeError, IndexError, ValueError, AttributeError) as _e:\\\\n    print(f\\\\\\\"[SSE] stream parse: {_e}\\\\\\\", file=sys.stderr)\\\\n    continue\\\\n```\\\\n\\\\nSo the `TypeError` IS caught, but it's in the outer handler. The `fired_indices` would have the index added BEFORE the `on_tool_ready` call, and the `continue` would skip to the next line in the stream.\\\\n\\\\nBut wait, no. The `fired_indices` is in the STREAM parser, not in the `_on_tool_ready` callback. Let me re-read:\\\\n\\\\n```python\\\\nfired_indices: set[int] = set()  # in _parse_stream\\\\n\\\\n# Inside the loop:\\\\nif on_tool_ready and idx not in fired_indices:\\\\n    ...\\\\n    try:\\\\n        json.loads(args)\\\\n        fired_indices.add(idx)  # <-- stream.py's fired_indices\\\\n        ready = dict(tc)\\\\n        ready[\\\\\\\"_index\\\\\\\"] = idx\\\\n        on_tool_ready(ready)  # <-- calls llm.py's _on_tool_ready\\\\n    except (json.JSONDecodeError, ValueError):\\\\n        pass\\\\n```\\\\n\\\\nAnd in llm.py's `_on_tool_ready`:\\\\n```python\\\\nexecuted_tool_indices: set[int] = set()  # in _api_call_phase\\\\n\\\\ndef _on_tool_ready(tc: dict) -> None:\\\\n    idx = tc.pop(\\\\\\\"_index\\\\\\\", -1)\\\\n    if idx in executed_tool_indices:\\\\n        return\\\\n    executed_tool_indices.add(idx)  # <-- llm.py's executed_tool_indices\\\\n    ...\\\\n    result = execute_tool(tc, ...)  # <-- if this raises TypeError...\\\\n    deferred_stream_results.append((tc, result))\\\\n```\\\\n\\\\nIf `execute_tool` raises TypeError:\\\\n1. stream.py's `fired_indices.add(idx)` - DONE\\\\n2. llm.py's `executed_tool_indices.add(idx)` - DONE\\\\n3. `deferred_stream_results.append(...)` - NOT DONE\\\\n4. Exception propagates to stream.py's outer handler, prints error, continues\\\\n\\\\nThen later in `_tool_execution_phase`:\\\\n```python\\\\nraw_tool_calls = msg[\\\\\\\"tool_calls\\\\\\\"]\\\\nremaining = [tc for i, tc in enumerate(raw_tool_calls) if i not in executed_tool_indices]\\\\n```\\\\n\\\\nSince `executed_tool_indices` includes the failed tool call's index, it's filtered OUT of `remaining`. So it won't be executed in the non-streaming path either.\\\\n\\\\nThen:\\\\n```python\\\\nif not remaining:\\\\n    messages.append(msg)  # assistant msg with tool_calls for ALL tools\\\\n    for tc, result in deferred_stream_results:\\\\n        _append_tool_result(...)  # only appends successful ones\\\\n    return False\\\\n```\\\\n\\\\nThe problem: `msg` (the assistant message) has tool_calls for ALL tools (including the failed one), but `deferred_stream_results` only has results for tools that didn't raise exceptions. So the failed tool's `tool_call_id` never gets a corresponding tool message!\\\\n\\\\nThis is the root cause! When `execute_tool` raises an exception during streaming (e.g., `_mcp_discover` missing gate args), the tool is marked as executed but no result is appended to messages. The next API call then includes the assistant message with the orphaned tool_call_id.\\\\n\\\\nNow, the second question is: **why does `execute_tool` raise TypeError for `_mcp_discover`?**\\\\n\\\\nLooking at the error: `_mcp_discover() missing 2 required positional arguments: '_write_gate' and '_read_gate'`\\\\n\\\\nThis means `_mcp_discover` is being called without the gate arguments. But `execute_tool` does pass them:\\\\n```python\\\\nfuture = executor.submit(dispatch, args, write_gate, read_gate)\\\\n```\\\\n\\\\nSo either:\\\\n1. The `dispatch` function stored in `_TOOL_DISPATCH[\\\\\\\"mcp_discover\\\\\\\"]` is NOT `_mcp_discover` (maybe an old version)\\\\n2. Or `_TOOL_DISPATCH[\\\\\\\"mcp_discover\\\\\\\"]` is some other function\\\\n\\\\nWait, but the `_register` decorator in `mcp_client.py` registers `_mcp_discover`. Let me verify: the `@_register(\\\\\\\"mcp_discover\\\\\\\")` decorator does `_TOOL_DISPATCH[name] = fn`. So `_TOOL_DISPATCH[\\\\\\\"mcp_discover\\\\\\\"] = _mcp_discover`.\\\\n\\\\nBut what if there's a DIFFERENT function also registered under the same name? Let me search.\\\\n\\\\nActually, wait. Let me re-read the error more carefully:\\\\n\\\\n```\\\\n[SSE] stream parse: _mcp_discover() missing 2 required positional arguments: '_write_gate' and '_read_gate'\\\\n```\\\\n\\\\nThe error is caught by stream.py's exception handler. The `on_tool_ready` callback is `_on_tool_ready` from llm.py. That callback calls `execute_tool(tc, write_gate, read_gate, ...)`. But if `execute_tool` raises a TypeError, it would be about the DISPATCH function, not about `_mcp_discover` directly. \\\\n\\\\nActually wait, the exception trace would show the dispatch function's name. Let me think...\\\\n\\\\n`