ment is that each `assistant(tool_calls)` is followed by matching `tool` messages BEFORE the next `assistant` (or `user`/`system`) message. So:\n\n```\nassistant(tool_calls=[A]), tool(A), assistant(text)  \u2190 valid\n```\n\nBut:\n```\nassistant(tool_calls=[A]), assistant(text), tool(A)  \u2190 INVALID\n```\n\nSo, when walking backwards and encountering a text-only assistant message, we CAN'T continue because what comes before it is a separate \"block\" \u2014 the tool results for the previous assistant(tool_calls) must come BEFORE the text-only assistant message.\n\nWait\u2026 actually, that's exactly the case where a text-only assistant would appear:\n\n```\n..., assistant(tool_calls=[A,B]), tool(A), tool(B), assistant(\"Here's a summary\"), assistant(tool_calls=[C])  [no tool(C)]\n```\n\nWalking backwards:\n1. assistant(tool_calls=[C]) \u2192 C not in seen_ids \u2192 orphan, strip_count=1\n2. assistant(\"Here's a summary\") \u2192 else \u2192 BREAK\n\nThis would strip the last assistant(tool_calls=[C]) but wouldn't look further back. Result: messages[:-1], which removes the orphaned one. Correct!\n\nBut what about:\n```\n..., assistant(tool_calls=[A,B]), tool(A), assistant(\"text\"), assistant(tool_calls=[C]), tool(C)\n```\n\nWalking backwards:\n1. tool(C) \u2192 seen_ids={C}\n2. assistant(tool_calls=[C]) \u2192 C in seen_ids \u2192 continue\n3. assistant(\"text\") \u2192 else \u2192 BREAK\n\nstops here. We never check assistant(tool_calls=[A,B]). But that's correct because:\n- B never got a tool result, but it's in a \"completed\" block (tool(A) and assistant(\"text\") come after it)\n- The API requirement is that tool results come immediately after the assistant(tool_calls), before the NEXT assistant message\n- Since assistant(\"text\") comes after tool(A), the sequence assistant(tool_calls=[A,B]), tool(A), assistant(\"text\") is already invalid for B\n\nSo the API would reject this payload regardless of what `_strip_orphaned_tool_calls` does.\n\nOK, so `_strip_orphaned_tool_calls` is actually working correctly for trailing orphans. Mid-chain orphans are already a structural problem that can't be fixed by stripping.\n\nNow I need to understand: is the orphan being created at the end (trailing) or in the middle?\n\nIf it's at the end (trailing), `_strip_orphaned_tool_calls` should catch it but apparently isn't. Let me check if there's a bug in the function...\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-read `_strip_orphaned_tool_calls` one more time with fresh eyes:\n\n```python\ndef _strip_orphaned_tool_calls(messages: list[dict]) -> list[dict]:\n    seen_ids: set[str] = set()\n    strip_count = 0\n    for i in range(len(messages) - 1, -1, -1):\n        m = messages[i]\n        role = m.get(\"role\", \"\")\n        if role == \"tool\":\n            tcid = m.get(\"tool_call_id\")\n            if tcid:\n                seen_ids.add(tcid)\n        elif role == \"assistant\" and \"tool_calls\" in m:\n            tc_ids = [tc.get(\"id\") for tc in m.get(\"tool_calls\", []) if tc.get(\"id\")]\n            if all(tcid in seen_ids for tcid in tc_ids):\n                continue\n            else:\n                strip_count += 1\n                continue\n        else:\n            break\n    if strip_count:\n        return messages[:-strip_count]\n    return messages\n```\n\nWait, there's a subtle bug! When we encounter an orphaned assistant(tool_calls), we increment `strip_count` and `continue`. But we DON'T add its tool_call_ids to `seen_ids`. So if there are two consecutive orphaned assistant messages:\n\n```\nassistant(tool_calls=[A]), assistant(tool_calls=[B])\n```\n\nWalking backwards:\n1. assistant(tool_calls=[B]) \u2192 B not in seen_ids \u2192 orphan, strip_count=1\n2. assistant(tool_calls=[A]) \u2192 A not in seen_ids \u2192 orphan, strip_count=2\n\nThen it hits the message before and breaks. Returns messages[:-2], stripping both. Correct!\n\nBut what about:\n```\nassistant(tool_calls=[A]), tool(A), assistant(tool_calls=[B])\n```\n\